annotation.TEXT: Helen Mirren is a respected British actress who has played three different English queens, including both Elizabeths.
Styrofoam is a brand of plastic foam frequently used as a packing material. Researchers found in 2015 that mealworms can live on a diet of nothing but Styrofoam.
In his heyday, Marlon Brando was one of the best-looking men in Hollywood, but as he got older, he began to put on the pounds and became the frequent butt of jokes for his increasing girth.
Sweet, but terrible stand up comedian, Fozzie Bear was a mainstay on The Muppets Show; he was performed by Frank OZ.
Teen detectives Joe and Frank Hardy were created by Edward Stratemeyer, who also invented Nancy Drew, Tom Swift, and the Bobbsey Twins.
A line from the song of the same name; Louis Prima paired it with “Just a Gigolo” in 1957, and the combination became a signature tune for him.
In the film Monty Python and the Holy Grail, a man trying to dump an elderly relative on a plague cart is repeatedly interrupted by his relative’s claims that he is not, in fact, dead.
A rendition of the “jungle native” chant from song “Hooked on a Feeling.” The chant was originally added to the existing song by Jonathan King.
Willy Water Bug is a sprinkler-like lawn toy first made by Wham-O in the ‘70s.
Iconic folk-rock musician, David Crosby struggled with his weight for many years, although he has slimmed down recently. McDonald’s introduced the McRib sandwich in 1981.
The first D cell batteries were introduced in 1898. During WWII the Navy decided to call them Type C batteries, confusing everyone.
Adventures of Pow Wow began as a local cartoon show in New York City in 1949.
Dance belts aren’t actually belts. They’re support garments for the genitals.
Actor, Al Lewis was best known for playing Grandpa Munster on The Munsters.
A line from the anti-war song “One Tin Soldier.” A version by Coven from the 1971 film Billy Jack became a hit that year.
Denny’s was originally called Danny’s Coffee Shops; they changed their name in 1959 to avoid confusing it with an LA chain, Coffee Dan’s.
Jessica McClure, or “Baby Jessica,” was 18 months old when she fell into a well in 1987. Rescuers worked frantically for three days before they pulled her out.
Eddie Bauer was born on Orcas Island and grew up exploring the Pacific Northwest before founding his clothing store chain.
RyKrisps were lightly salted, baked rye crackers manufactured in Minneapolis; they were phased out in 2015.
Sox Appeal is a chain of mall stores based in Minneapolis that sell nothing but socks. Kinko’s (now FedEx Office) is a national chain of printing/copying stores.
AccuWeather provides weather forecasts to local news stations and other clients. It was founded in 1962 by a grad student in meteorology.
Aaron Fechter, inventor of Whac-a-Mole, also created the animatronic band for ShowBiz Pizza Place (later Chuck E. Cheese).
“Calgon, take me away” is a longtime ad slogan for Calgon scented bath products, which include bubble bath, body lotions, and more.
One version of an old military marching cadence, or jody call; there are a number of variations.
The DustBuster was first marketed unsuccessfully to men as the Spot Vac. When women kept borrowing them, the company relaunched it as the DustBuster and sold millions.
The three weird sisters predicted Macbeth’s rise and eventual fall in the Shakespeare play Macbeth. “Weird” derives from the Old English “wyrd,” or “fate.”
The tiny blue Smurfs were originally Belgian comic book characters in the ‘50s; they became a hugely popular fad in the ‘70s and ‘80s as collectible figurines.
In The Empire Strikes Back, Han Solo eviscerates a tauntaun on the ice planet Hoth to keep Luke Skywalker from freezing to death.
Uriah Heep was a popular British prog-metal band in the ‘70s. The band’s name is taken from a character in the Charles Dickens novel David Copperfield.
Several Moody Blues songs have lyrics about emerging from darkness into the light, including “One Step into the Light” and “Lost in a Lost World.”
Bozo was a children’s show franchise that aired from 1949-2001; many different actors played the balding clown, but the most famous was Chicago’s Bob Bell.
Carousel is a Rodgers and Hammerstein musical about a carnival barker who attempts a robbery to support his pregnant girlfriend.
A line from the song “Footprints in the Snow,” a signature song for bluegrass musician Bill Monroe.
In ancient Rome, the 6 Vestal Virgins served the hearth goddess Vesta for 30-year terms. They could marry later, but few did.
Think you know every reference in The Mole People? Test your knowledge as we call them all out.
William Faulkner was a Nobel Prize-winning novelist (The Sound and the Fury, As I Lay Dying) who also wrote screenplays for Hollywood.
Freeze-dried ice cream was developed for NASA but only went to space once, aboard Apollo 7. The astronauts hated it.
According to ancient Greek myth, the poisonous waters of the River Styx would eat through any container except one made from a horse’s hoof.
Maybelline was named after the founder's sister, Mabel.
An imitation of comedian Jackie Gleason’s catchphrase from his variety show, The Jackie Gleason Show.
Actor, Hugh Beaumont’s best-known part was playing all-American Father, Ward Cleaver on the sitcom Leave It to Beaver.
Early ‘90s TV ads for Minneapolis mega-mall Mall of America showed its cavernous interior and sang “There’s a place for fun in your life …”
“Monster Mash” was a smash hit novelty song in 1962 by Bobby “Boris” Pickett and the Crypt-Kickers.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Chariots of the Gods? inspired many works of fiction, including the original Battlestar Galactica.
David Soul played Hutch on the TV series Starsky & Hutch. In 1982, he was charged with battery after assaulting his third wife in their Bel Air home.
Skokie and Downers Grove are both suburbs of Chicago: Skokie to the north, and Downers Grove to the west.
Labor organizer, Cesar Chavez worked to better the lives of migrant farm workers, founding the National Farm Workers Association and spearheading a five-year strike by grape pickers.
Bakers in the mountains must alter their recipes to compensate for the lower air pressure. Usually you don’t need to worry about it until you hit about 3,000 feet above sea level.
Nike’s famous ad slogan was inspired by the last words of executed killer Gary Gilmore: “Let’s do it.”
On the ‘60s sitcom The Munsters, Lily was the vampiric housewife played by Yvonne De Carlo.
A line from the song “Oh, What a Beautiful Mornin’,” from the musical Oklahoma!
The Donner Party in 1846 and the 1972 Andes flight disaster were both situations in which people stranded on snowy mountain terrain resorted to cannibalism to survive.
The Sherpas are a Nepalese ethnic group famous as expert mountain climbers in the Himalayas; Sherpas regularly help guide expeditions up Mt. Everest.
Mt. Pinatubo is a volcano in the Philippines. In 1991, for the first time in 600 years, it erupted, killing more than 800 people and leaving 100,000 homeless.
“Baby Got Back” is a song by rap artist, Sir Mix-A-Lot celebrating prominent female posteriors.
A standard golf course has 18 holes, but if players are pressed for time or the weather looks bad, they have the option of playing only half the course.
On March 15, 44 BCE (aka the Ides of March), Julius Caesar was murdered by a group of conspirators led by Cassius. Marc Anthony was not involved; he succeeded Caesar as ruler of the Roman Empire.
The logo of W.L. Gore and Associates, makers of Gore-Tex, looks like a notched arrow.
Did we miss any references? Be sure to let us know in the comments!
The name of cosmetics company Lancôme Paris was taken from the ruins of a castle, Le Chateau de Lancosme.
“The Ballad of Jed Clampett” was sung by country-western star Jerry Scoggins; the instrumentals were provided by the bluegrass duo Flatt and Scruggs.
The original “Hang in There, Baby” cat poster came out in 1971 and featured photographer Victor Baldwin’s Siamese kitten Sassy.
Culottes are a type of trousers ending just below the knee; they were fashionable for upper-class men from the late Middle Ages through the early 19th century.
A dry-vac, also called a wet/dry-vac, is a powerful vacuum cleaner used in workshops and basements.
“Dangerously thin” was a constant criticism of mid-‘90s supermodels like Kate Moss, who personified “heroin chic.”
Sneezy was one of the seven dwarfs in the Walt Disney film Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs. He was voiced by Billy Gilbert.
Let us know if we missed any references!
A reference to the song “The Lonely Goatherd” from The Sound of Music.
The Quad Cities are a group of four cities clustered along I-80 in the Midwest: Moline, Illinois; Rock Island, Illinois; Davenport, Iowa; and Bettendorf, Iowa.
The Mole People: Fully annotated by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Singer Madonna has cultivated an image as a confident, sex-positive woman, as in her 1992 book Sex, which featured nude photos of herself, other celebrities, and models.
A riff o the lyrics fro the pp song, "Alright, Okay, You Win", first recorded by singer Peggy Lee in 1958 and becoming one of her signature songs.
“Chopsticks” (original title “The Celebrated Chop Waltz”) is an extremely simple waltz for piano, crudely banged out with two fingers, written by Euphemia Allen in 1877.
Recipes for s’mores appeared as early as the ‘20s, although they were not called “s’mores” until the ‘30s.
The Minnesota Valley Canning Co. began using the Green Giant mascot in 1928; they later renamed their company after the ad figure.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
Mervyn’s was a discount department store chain; it went under in 2008.
Abolitionist, John Brown staged a failed 1859 raid on a federal arsenal in Harpers Ferry, Virginia, in hopes of inciting a slave rebellion. He was convicted of treason and hanged.
The Venus de Milo was carved around 120 B.C.E. by an unknown sculptor and discovered in 1820 on Milos, an island in the Aegean.
Lt. Commander Data, the pale-skinned android on Star Trek: TNG, has had several songs written in his honor, including “The Positronic Pimp” and “The Sexy Data Tango.”
Before Times Square got all Disneyfied, it was largely known for hookers, massage parlors, adult bookstores, and porn theaters. But SexWorld is actually an adult store in Minneapolis.
Brace yourself. It's time for the full-annotated Mole People.
El Greco was a 16th-century Spanish painter who was far ahead of his time; his paintings gained new renown in the 20th century.
An impression of Jane Hathaway (Nancy Kulp), assistant to greedy banker Mr. Milburn Drysdale on The Beverly Hillbillies.
Bespectacled silent film comedian, Harold Lloyd was known for physical comedy featuring an array of life-threatening stunts, which he performed himself.
If we missed any references, let us know!
Seattle dentist, Barney Clark was the world's first artificial heart recipient, in 1982. He lived (unhappily) for 112 days attached to a 400-pound compressor.
Like other married TV couples of the ‘60s, Ward and June Cleaver slept in prim, sexless twin beds.
Patti LaBelle is one of the diva queens of contemporary music, best known for her disco hit “Lady Marmalade.”
Most jokes about the cowardice of the French date back to WWII, when France surrendered to Nazi Germany in 1940.
Solarcaine is a brand name for lidocaine, a local anesthetic; it is sold OTC to relieve the pain of sunburn.
Cindy Lou Who, “who was no more than two,” is a child in the classic TV special How the Grinch Stole Christmas!, based on the book by Dr. Seuss.
Cardinal Stritch University is a Catholic university in Milwaukee. It was originally a women’s college, going fully coed in 1970.
Gershenson worked in film for nearly 50 years, starting in the silent era, when he conducted orchestras in movie theaters. He earned two Oscar nods; neither was for this film.
The comic strip “Family Circus” periodically published cartoons that looked as if they were drawn by a small child, claiming they were drawn by “Billy,” the seven-year-old son in the strip.
On TV cooking shows, the host will often demonstrate how to prepare a dish and then haul out another version baked earlier to show what it looks like once it's finished.
Actor Jack Nicholson, according to various tell-all memoirs, allegedly hosted days-long, drug-fueled sex parties in the ‘70s and ‘80s that made the Playboy Mansion look like a Baptist retreat.
Before appearing on Batman, Alan Napier was a classically trained actor who starred in feature film versions of Macbeth and Julius Caesar.
No Fear is a clothing company popular in the ‘90s; its clothing has its logo prominently emblazoned on it, and its brand is associated with extreme sports.
Sensurround was a gimmick used to hype the film Earthquake by using high-decibel sound to shake the audience. The effect bled over into neighboring theaters and disturbed patrons.
A little of the iconic hard rock guitar riff from the Deep Purple song “Lazy.”
“Stupid Girl” is a 1996 song by Garbage, their biggest US hit.
American painter Robert Motherwell was one of the founders of the Abstract Expressionism movement. He liked to paint big black blobs on a plain background.
A riff on the song “Housequake,” by the artist formerly known as, then known once again as, Prince, from his 1987 album Sign o’ the Times.
Kristen McMenamy is a fashion model who in the '90s cultivated a pale androgynous look.
In the ‘50s, Tupperware molds in various shapes to make your Jell-O look fancy became popular.
The film Norma Rae starred Sally Field as a young woman trying to unionize her textile mill. It was based on real-life union organizer Crystal Lee Sutton.
Fudge Stripes, shortbread cookies covered with stripes of fudge, are a variety of cookie made by Keebler.
There are about 3 million regular bridge players in the US. In the ‘40s, about 44 percent of American households had at least one bridge player.
Visions of Light is an award-winning 1993 documentary on the history of cinematography.
Walt Disney was an animator, producer, and theme-park impresario, including Walt Disney World in Orlando, Florida.
In 1923, mountaineer George Mallory was asked why he wanted to climb the so-far-unconquered Mt. Everest. He replied, “Because it’s there.” He froze to death during his 1924 attempt.
A line from the Grateful Dead son "Dark Hollow". Though originally written and recorded by Bill Browning, the Grateful Dead version became far more popular.
Shurfine is a generic brand of grocery products distributed nationally by Topco Associates.
In ancient Rome, the 6 Vestal Virgins served the hearth goddess Vesta for 30-year terms. They could marry later, but few did.
The Hekawi were the local Indian tribe led by Chief Wild Eagle on the ‘60s TV sitcom F Troop.
The Frappuccino was actually developed at the Massachusetts coffeehouse chain, The Coffee Connection, which Starbucks bought in 1994.
Sam’s Club is a members-only chain of warehouse stores that sell great whacking boxes of things at relatively modest prices.
The theme song was a variation on the so-called “warpath” music Hollywood used for Native Americans, likely derived from music used by Great Plains and Southwest tribes.
Coors Light ran a series of TV ads in the ‘90s that showed giant people—and sometimes a giant dog—playing various sports among the Rocky Mountains.
A line from the theme song for the cartoon Adventures of Pow Wow.
A line from TLC’s 1995 song “Waterfalls,” which became the group’s second #1 hit.
In 1996, a human rights group reported that sweatshop labor was being used to make a clothing line under TV host Kathie Lee Gifford’s name.
The OTC asthma treatment Primatene Mist was banned in the US after 2011 because it contains CFCs.
In this context, “stories” refers to TV soap operas, which originated on radio in the ‘30s and made the jump to TV in the late ‘40s.
Sweet and spicy mole sauce (pronounced MOW-lay) is a popular item in Mexican cuisine.
The Clorox Co. was originally called the Electro-Alkaline Co. when it was founded in 1913.
Dr. Zachary Smith, as played by Jonathan Harris, was the mincing stowaway/saboteur on the campy sci-fi TV series Lost in Space.
On the TV show Batman, Alfred’s last name, Pennyworth, was never mentioned. He was always just “Alfred.”
In the old Laurel and Hardy comedy films, Oliver Hardy often reproved Stan Laurel with the line, "Well, here's another nice mess you've gotten me into."
A riff on the song “Get Up, Get Down, Get Funky, Get Loose,” performed by Teddy Pendergrass.
The “pockets” of pocket gophers are their large cheek pouches, which can be turned inside out and are used for hauling food back to their underground burrows.
A cotillion is a formal dance held during the debutante season to present the debs to society.
An imitation of Ricky Ricardo objecting to one of Lucy’s hair-brained schemes on I Love Lucy.
Visa began in 1958 as a Bank of America pilot program and chose its name in 1976 as a familiar term in many languages.
The Man Who Skied Down Everest is a documentary about Japanese skier Yuichiro Miura, who, armed with a parachute, skied down the Lhotse face of Mt. Everest in 1970.
Sun tea is a way of making iced tea in which the sun provides the heat for brewing. Lipton made large glass containers specifically for sun tea.
Are You There God? It’s Me, Margaret is a 1970 children’s book by Judy Blume, about a young girl dealing with her spiritual doubts and her burgeoning adolescence.
Ishtar was a notorious Hollywood flop, a road movie about two lounge singers who get mixed up in a CIA plot. It cost $51 million and only made $14 million.
Diminutive actress Linda Hunt won an Oscar for her portrayal of male photographer Billy Kwan in The Year of Living Dangerously.
To be fair, he said “pilgrim” 23 times in Liberty Valance, so that’s a lot.
In the ‘90s a welfare-reform bill was pushed through Congress that emphasized “workfare,” which focuses on training and work experience programs.
Bain de Soleil is a brand of sunscreen; the name is French for “sun bathing.”
In a professional kitchen, the sous chef (French for “under-chef”) is the second in command under the executive chef, and usually the next in line for that position.
In the Edgar Allan Poe story “The Cask of Amontillado,” the narrator lures a friend into his cellar by promising him Amontillado (a fine dry sherry) and then walls him up alive.
Retired astronaut Shannon Lucid went into space five times, including a long stay on the Mir space station in 1996.
British, fashion designer Vivienne Westwood dressed the Sex Pistols and brought punk style into the fashion world.
“Wedgievision” is meant to evoke such ‘50s cinema gimmicks as Vistavision, Smell-O-Vision, and HypnoVista.
A line from the song “Whip It” by Devo.
In the ‘80s, the federal government launched a program to get food to the needy, and thanks to huge dairy subsidies, it had massive warehouses full of cheese, so that’s what they got.
One theory on the origin of golf course sand traps holds that they evolved from sheep bedding down behind sand dunes near early courses, which dug out natural hollows over time.
“Strong enough for a man, but made for a woman” is the longtime ad slogan of Secret deodorant.
Starbucks roasts more than 500 million pounds of coffee beans every year.
Dr. Smith's relentless cowardice on Lost in Space resulted in frequent emotional breakdowns, in which he would confess his shortcomings and whimper, "Oh, the shame, the pain..."
Mole People star John Agar appeared in six films with John Wayne, including Fort Apache and She Wore a Yellow Ribbon.
On the ‘80s sequel series The New Leave It to Beaver, Ward and June’s two sons, Wally and Beaver, each have two children of their own.
An imitation of comedian, Dana Carvey’s SNL parody of political commentator John McLaughlin, the firebrand moderator of The McLaughlin Group.
The video log of TV production company Mark VII Limited showed an arm wielding a hammer to stamp the Mark VII logo into stone.
In the Monty Python film, Life of Brian, a Roman jailor spits in Brian’s face, and his cellmate mocks him as a “proper little jailor’s pet.”
The leader of the Keebler Elves in their ads is a put-upon elf named Ernest J. Keebler.
F. Scott Fitzgerald was a novelist known for his portrait of the Jazz Age in such books as The Great Gatsby; Fitzgerald also worked as a screenwriter for a time.
Shirley Manson is the lead singer for the band Garbage.
“A man, a plan, a canal: Panama” is a famous palindrome, as is Gorog’s last name. “Panama” was first published by Leigh Mercer in 1948.
Eduard Shevardnadze was foreign minister of the USSR in the late ‘80s. He resigned abruptly in 1990 to protest the influence of old-style Communist hard-liners.
A reference to the song “We Built This City” by Starship, née Jefferson Starship, née Jefferson Airplane.
A paraphrase of a line from Dr. Seuss’s classic children’s tale How the Grinch Stole Christmas!
On Happy Days, Arthur “Fonzie” Fonzarelli was at first allowed to wear his iconic leather jacket only while on or near his bike, so producers kept him on it constantly, even indoors.
The Canadian slang term “hoser” was popularized by Bob and Doug McKenzie (Rick Moranis and Dave Thomas) on the “Great White North” segments of SCTV.
The jingle for Northwest Orient Airlines, as heard in a series of ads in the ‘70s and ‘80s until it dropped “Orient” from its name in 1986.
Switzerland, despite its famed neutrality, maintains an army for self-defense—the origin of the fabled Swiss Army knife.
Officially known as Stereo 8, 8-tracks were cassettes of magnetic tape in an infinite loop first sold in 1964. They were among the first portable music media.
Kwai Chang Caine (played by David Carradine) was the young Shaolin monk who traveled the American West helping people and kicking booty in the TV series Kung Fu.
On the TV series Sanford and Son, when Fred Sanford wanted to manipulate his son, he would fake a heart attack and call to his dead wife, “It’s the big one! I’m comin’, Lizabeth!”
In the campy ‘60s TV series Batman, Alan Napier, who plays the high priest Elinu in The Mole People, played Bruce Wayne’s loyal Butler, Alfred Pennyworth.
This is the catch phrase of flamenco guitarist María del Rosario Pilar Martínez Molina Baeza de Rasten, who goes by the stage name of Charo.
A riff on the Belinda Carlisle song “Heaven Is a Place on Earth,” her most popular tune; it hit #1 in 1987.
A reference to the Led Zeppelin song “Thank You”: “If the sun refused to shine, I would still be loving you/When mountains crumble to the sea …”
Zig-Zag is a French brand of cigarette rolling paper, often associated with making joints.
Philosopher, Hannah Arendt coined the phrase “the banality of evil” in her best-known work, Eichmann in Jerusalem. She wrote extensively on violence and totalitarianism.
The spectacular failure of New Coke in the ‘80s is a prime example of focus group data gone wrong—it tested well in focus groups but bombed in the marketplace.
The “vapors” was a catchall malady of women in Victorian Britain and the pre-Civil War Deep South, which could cover anything from depression to PMS.
Satirical author Jerzy Kosinski (Steps, Being There) committed suicide in 1991 by ODing on drugs and alcohol and then suffocating himself with a plastic bag on his head.
Francis the Talking Mule, a forerunner of the more famous Mister Ed, appeared in a string of movies in the ‘50s.
The so-called “warpath” music was first performed in the 1910s for Buffalo Bill’s circus and was later adapted for Hollywood.
Comedian/actor Adam Sandler enjoyed amazing success with a series of lowbrow, feel-good movies, including The Wedding Singer and Mr. Deeds.
Jheri curls, a “wet look” style popular in the ‘80s, were named after hairstylist Jheri Redding.
A paraphrase of a line from the theme song to the TV sitcom The Beverly Hillbillies: “And up through the ground came a-bubblin’ crude.”
The origin of the Santa Claus legend is thought to lie in stories about St. Nicholas, a 4th-century Christian saint. (“Sinterklaas” is the Dutch name for St. Nick.)
When a college student decides not to take a class he or she had enrolled in, there is a bit of paperwork involved: a "drop sheet," which the professor has to sign.
Wacky immigrant Balki Bartokomous was one of the main characters on the sitcom Perfect Strangers; he was played by Bronson Pinchot.
Auntie Mame is a play and film based on the Patrick Dennis novel about the eccentric aunt of a young orphan; Rosalind Russell played the part on stage and screen.
Thanks for watching the fully-annotated Mole People.
Emo Philips is a standup comedian from the wacked-out Andy Kaufman school of comedy.
Swiss psychiatrist Elisabeth Kübler-Ross proposed the five stages of grief in 1969: denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and finally acceptance.
Explorer, Will Steger has led multiple polar expeditions, including the first confirmed dogsled trip to the North Pole and the first dogsled crossing of Antarctica.
Actress Kitty Carlisle was best known for her appearances as a panelist on the game show To Tell the Truth.
From 1950-60, the famous Pantages Theatre on the corner of Hollywood & Vine hosted the Academy Awards—including the first televised ceremony in 1953.
Sam Spade was the harder-than-hardboiled protagonist of the Dashiell Hammett detective novel The Maltese Falcon; he was played by Humphrey Bogart in the 1941 film.
“Gentlemen, start your engines” is the traditional announcement made at the beginning of auto races.
An imitation of the pompous criminologist from the cult classic The Rocky Horror Picture Show, explaining how to do "The Time Warp."
Chariots of the Gods? is a book by Erich Von Daniken, in which he postulated that the pyramids of ancient Egypt were built with extraterrestrial assistance.
The official uniform of Klansmen is a set of white robes and a pointed white mask, used to conceal the identities of the members.
Minnesota and Wisconsin boast multiple towns and lakes named Bass Lake. Then there are the ones in California and North Carolina. Seems to be a popular name.
The “Cossack Dance” song is actually titled “Korobeiniki.” Korobeiniki were peddlers who sold their wares from trays; the song tells of a doomed love affair between a peddler and a peasant girl.
“Pilgrim” was cowboy actor John Wayne’s most recognizable catchphrase.
The opening title sequence of The Mod Squad showed hip young police narcs Linc, Julie, and Pete running breathlessly through a narrow, dark, rain-soaked alley.
A snood hold a woman's hair in either a cloth or a loosely knitted or crocheted bag. It has been popular at various points in history, including the medieval era, the Victorian period, and the 1940s.
Sunlight Hand Dishwashing Liquid boasts that it has “the grease-cutting power of real lemon juice.” Also diethanolamine, sodium xylene sulfonate, and dodecylbenzene sulfonic acid.
“Veni, vidi, vici” (“I came, I saw, I conquered” in Latin) is how Julius Caesar laconically reported to Rome that he had won a military victory over the king of Pontus in 47 B.C.E.
In-N-Out Burger is a California-based chain of fast-food restaurants that inspires an almost cult-like devotion in its many fans.
In the Catholic Church, special intention involves holding a Mass or saying prayers for a specific purpose, such as helping parishioners who are having health or financial problems.
How Green Was My Valley is a book by Richard Llewellyn about a valley in Wales ruined by the coal-mining industry; it was made into a film in 1941.
Starting in the ‘20s, Lysol disinfectant ran ads urging women to use it as a douche to eliminate odors. Five women died and nearly 200 were poisoned because they failed to dilute it enough.
A line from the song “Who Will Buy” from the 1960 musical Oliver!, based on the novel Oliver Twist by Charles Dickens.
Tommy G. Thompson was governor of Wisconsin for 14 years. In 1996 he pushed through a welfare-reform program that required recipients to work.
Cheap Trick is a rock band most popular in the late ‘70s with albums like Cheap Trick at Budokan and Dream Police, although they enjoyed a comeback in the late ‘90s.
The Keebler elves supposedly bake all of Keebler’s cookies. There have been many over the years, including Flo the accountant, Roger the jeweler, and Buckets the fudge guy.
Bingo is based on a canival game from the '20s called Beano, which itself was a variation of Lotto, a French game dating to the 18th century.
Billy Madison starred Adam Sandler as the son of a very wealthy man, who, in order to inherit, must repeat grades 1-12.
The phrase “drank the Kool-Aid” dates back to the 1978 deaths in Jonestown, Guyana, when 900+ cultists committed mass suicide/murder. In fact, the cult used Flavor Aid.
The Nutty Professor is a film starring Jerry Lewis as a nerdy professor who invents a potion that transforms him into a suave ladies’ man.
A line from the WB cartoon Ali Baba Bunny. Pismo Beach once claimed to be the “Clam Capital of the World,” but the clam population has been decimated by overharvesting and sea otters.
The song “High Hopes,” from the Frank Sinatra movie A Hole in the Head, became the theme song for JFK’s 1960 presidential campaign, with slightly altered lyrics.
Björk is an Icelandic musician and actress, known for her eclectic soprano voice and her outrageous fashion sense.
“You want it when?!” is the caption to a cartoon of a group of people laughing hysterically; it appears to be by Henry Syverson, who often drew for the Saturday Evening Post.
Pig Latin is a “language game” in which English words are reconstructed according to a simple set of rules. The current version dates back to at least 1919.
The Chunnel under the English Channel between Great Britain and France is the longest undersea tunnel in the world. It opened for passenger and freight traffic in 1994.
The main Hormel meatpacking facility is located in Austin, Minnesota, near its southern border with Iowa.
“Made it, Ma! Top of the world!” is a famous line from the extra-noir gangster film White Heat, starring James Cagney.
An imitation of Venice Beach rapper Dr. Geek in the infomercials for BluBlocker sunglasses, which ran in the ‘90s.
“Have You Never Been Mellow” is a 1975 song by Olivia Newton-John, her second #1 hit in the US.
Data was unaffected by disease, the vacuum of space, and other human frailties, but he was vulnerable to computer viruses, energy overloads, and the fatal remote “off switch.”
Wayne only used the phrase in two films—McClintock and The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance.
An imitation of school closing announcements made over the radio during inclement weather.
In the ‘60s, underground chemist Owsley Stanley was the first individual to manufacture large quantities of extremely pure and potent LSD.
A line from the song “After the Lovin’” by Englebert Humperdinck, a top 10 hit for him in 1977.
This phrase, which first appeared in print in 1952, pops up on plaques, trivets, samplers, etc., in cutesy homes that favor country crafts and potpourri.
The Mach 1 is a “performance” (read: faster) version of the Mustang introduced with the 1969 model of the iconic American sports car.
Jerry Garcia of the Grateful Dead was known for his meandering, interminable guitar solos during live performances. Liturgical dance is dance as a form of worship during a religious ceremony.
Actor George Hamilton’s ultra-tanned complexion has resembled chestnut-brown leather for decades. He was unsurprisingly treated for skin cancer in 2011.
Chuck Knoblauch played second base for the Minnesota Twins from 1991-97. His career batting average was .289.
Ward and June Cleaver were held up as the improbably ideal American marriage; Beaumont and Billingsley had 2 divorces and 4 spouses between them (2 of Billingsley’s husbands died).
Interesting trivia: this fanciful word for a doohickey first appeared in print in 1750!
